<!-- COSTS LAW -->
<section class="section" id="costs" aria-labelledby="costs-heading">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="costs-inner">
      <div class="costs-body">
        <p class="section-label">Specialist Area</p>
        <h2 id="costs-heading">Costs Law and Fixed Costs Regimes</h2>
        <div class="section-rule" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <p>Costs law is central to Henry King's practice. Ranked in the Legal 500 2025 as having an "encyclopaedic knowledge of costs law," he appears for both receiving and paying parties at all levels of costs assessment — including solicitor and client costs — and has been instructed unled in assessments worth in excess of seven figures.</p>
        <p>His costs work spans high-value commercial matters, judicial reviews, insurance disputes, contentious and non-contentious solicitor/client costs, and injury-related claims including the large bills often associated with clinical negligence. He is familiar with the old and new fixed costs regimes and advises on the tactical considerations that arise from them, particularly in relation to Part 36 offers.</p>
        <p>Henry has provided training to the Association of Costs Lawyers on costs budgeting and regularly appears in CCMCs, including in the High Court. He has appeared in the SCCO on both procedural matters and detailed assessments, and has advised on assessments in excess of £4 million.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="costs-callout">
        <h3>Costs Practice at a Glance</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Detailed and summary assessment (SCCO and all levels)</li>
          <li>Solicitor/client costs — contentious and non-contentious</li>
          <li>Retainer disputes and CFA compliance</li>
          <li>Fixed costs — old and new regimes, Part 36 tactics</li>
          <li>Non-party costs orders and wasted costs</li>
          <li>Security for costs applications</li>
          <li>Costs budgeting and CCMCs</li>
          <li>Litigation funding and third-party recovery</li>
          <li>QOCS — applications to set aside, mixed claims, fundamental dishonesty</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

